post_text:
Hendrick Hospice Care is pleased to present Club Courage, a six-week grief support group for children ages kindergarten through 12th grade who have experienced a loss through death, divorce, separation, incarceration or deployment. Children participate in activities that promote self-esteem, encourage self-healing, and provide an outlet for unexpressed emotions. The supportive environment helps each child develop healthy coping skills through a variety of grief exercises.

Club Courage will meet every Tuesday from October 6th through November 10th from 7 p.m. to 8 p.m. at our Hendrick Hospice Care facility located at 1651 Pine Street. This program is free of charge and open to the community.
Interested parents/guardians to go to hendrickhospice.org/clubcourage find out more information or to register

post_text:
FREE LUNCH FOR EVERY STUDENT!
Beginning September 8th, all students will receive lunch at no charge. Last week, USDA released flexibility to ensure all children have access to nutritious food as the country recovers from the COVID-19 pandemic. Late Friday afternoon, TDA released guidance to school districts on how this could be implemented. We have opted into these waivers retro-active to Tuesday, September 8th. Students who paid for lunch yesterday will be credited. Money that is in accounts will remain in accounts for future use. FREE MEALS WILL CONTINUE UNTIL DECEMBER 31, 2020 OR UNTIL FUNDING RUNS OUT.

post_text: Thank you for your patience with dismissal yesterday and there are going to be adjustments for today’s release. 1st change will be the entrance and traffic directions once in the parking lot. Next will be the release times and loading. PreK will release at 3:25 and all other grades will release at 3:35. In the cafeteria parking lot you will enter the far in as usual and be directed through the lot in an S pattern then we will utilize two lanes for pick up, see map. In the MS parking lot you will enter the far end and use a pick up lane and exit lane to leave how you came in. Again see map. Also if grades 2nd and below have an older sibling they will be all grouped together and picked up at the MS gym parking lot/awning instead of having to pick up at two spots. Again we will release K-6 at 3:35. Thank you for your patience as we work through this new process. Please look at the map on Facebook and the Livestream before coming this afternoon.

Eula Independent School District
PRIVATE NONPROFIT SCHOOL NOTIFICATION

Eula Independent School District will be providing information to private nonprofit schools, within the school district’s boundaries, that would like to learn about participating in Title I, Part A services. Title I, Part A is a federal program intended to assist schools in meeting the academic needs of struggling students.

The meeting will be held via ZOOM at 10:00 am on Thursday, June 29th, 2020.

SENIORS!!!

We need you to come and turn-in all of your school issued equipment and clean out all of your things from the building. Your time is Tuesday, May 19 @ 12:30. We will have a class meeting at 1:30. At that meeting we will discuss plans for graduation.

I know that the end of this year did not turn out the way anyone could have predicted, and that you have missed many things. On a positive note, you will be remembered as a class that had a senior year like no other. I hope that you understand how much everyone up here at school cares about you, and we hope that the graduation we have planned is something you will remember forever. I know that I will. I look forward to seeing all of you tomorrow.

Thanks

Mr. Damron

post_text: The Governor announced today that all schools will remain closed for the remainder of the school year. This is tough news to handle for our staff and teachers that miss our students. We are especially sad for our graduating seniors. Eula ISD will continue to provide remote instruction for the remainder of the school year. We will be in touch as soon as possible with a plan for end of year activities for our students. (Graduations, proms, end of year device returns, etc.) Together, we will continue to work through this situation, and focus on the well being of our students, staff, and community. #PiratePride

post_text: Eula Jr. High students competed in the Regional TCEA Robotics competition on Saturday at ACU. Sanjana Peterson, Kinsey Lawrence, and Sophie Abril placed 1st in the Intermediate Division. John Powers and Riley Johnson placed 1st in the Advanced Division, and Katie McCollum and Clayton Gray placed 2nd. All these students qualified for the State Competition. Other competitors included Hunter Spohn, Caysen Smith, Hailie Cauthen, Carly Newman, Layla Fostel, Laney Fostel, and Ava Millette. Congratulations to Sponsor Toby Christian and all Pirate competitors.

post_text: More pictures from the Veterans Program
text: More pictures from the Veterans Program

post_text:
We had an amazing opportunity today celebrating this great country we live in by honoring our local veterans. Eula's 2020 senior class used this 75th Anniversary of World War II to recognize our veterans from that era and the sacrifices they made. Out of the 16 million Americans who served in WWII, less than 380,000 are alive today. It is estimated that around 300 WWII veterans die each day.

Our Pirate Band presented a powerful presentation of patriotic music under the direction of Carl Hooper. Kindergarten, 3rd and 5th grade as well as our Elementary Leadership team performed songs and poetry to honor our special guests.

Nancy Galle and Thomas Rock, both Eula graduates, honored thier fathers' Hicks Turner and Claude Rock, both WWII veterans. The crowd enjoyed memories of their fathers' experiences and heroism.

Keynote speaker was Mr. Walter Nicolds, curator of the Dyess Airforce Museum.

Thank you to all our veterans for your service.
